If I write<p><pre><code>  if ((1 << 33) == 0) {
    // whatever
  }
</code></pre>
I&#x27;m fine with my program crashing. I&#x27;m not fine with my compiler simply assuming this cannot happen, and removing the whole `if` statement.

Instead we should maybe argue how undefined variable and undefined behaviour handling in LLVM is making things worse than they actually could be:<p>Undef variables taking on different values at different use points can lead to e.g. a == a being false. Code paths being possible with undefined values, that wouldn&#x27;t be possible with any value sounds like a terrible idea to me, possibly exploitable, at least a source for heisenbugs<p>When llvm finds undefined behaviour in a code path (not possible undefined behaviour, but there actually is undefined behaviour), it does strange things instead of just trapping. When the execution reaches that code path, the program already is in an erroneous state, no need to optimize stuff there.<p>For instance:<p>int main(int argc, char <i></i> argv) {
int a = 1;
int b = 0;
printf(&quot;%d&quot;, a/b);
}<p>compiles to:<p>define i32 @main(i32 %argc, i8<i></i> nocapture readnone %argv) #0 {
%1 = tail call i32 (i8<i>, ...)</i> @printf(i8* getelementptr inbounds ([3 x i8]* @.str, i64 0, i64 0), i32 undef) #2
ret i32 0
}<p>Why let the program behave buggy when llvm can see that undefined behaviour will occur? Why not just trap instead? That would have zero cost.
